                <head>205. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Presidential Press Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HJC1">James
                    Hagerty</persName>’s diary entry for April 12–20, a period which the President
                    spent in Augusta, Georgia, states that Admiral <persName corresp="#p_SAFB1"
                        >Felix B. Stump</persName>, Commander in Chief, Pacific, who was in
                    Washington briefly for consultations, met with the President on April 16.
                        <persName corresp="#p_HJC1">Hagerty</persName>’s diary entry reads in part
                    as follows:</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“<persName corresp="#p_SAFB1">Stump</persName> flew down to Augusta, arriving
                        at the airport at 8:00 A.M. Draper and I met him and brought him to the
                        National, arriving there at 8:30. The President and <persName
                            corresp="#p_SAFB1">Stump</persName> had a private conversation for one
                        hour. It mainly dealt with the build-up which the Chinese Communists are
                        conducting on the Mainland opposite Quemoy and Matsu. Aerial reconnaissance
                        has shown that the Communists are moving in fighter aircraft, including jets
                        and moving some of their bases. Neither <persName corresp="#p_SAFB1"
                            >Stump</persName> nor the President believe that an attack is directly
                        imminent, although the Chinese Corns are increasing their potential.”
                            (<persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_HJC1">Hagerty</persName> Papers)</p>
                </quote>
            </div>
